---

Since overriding `getClass().getSimpleName()` is not possible, the better fix is to change the expected message to match the actual exception message, which is the simple name of the anonymous subclass (empty string).

So the fixed test is:

```java
package com.google.gson;
import static org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions.assertEquals;
import static org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions.assertThrows;

import org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;

class JsonElementTest {

  @Test
  void testGetAsDouble_throwsUnsupportedOperationException() {
    JsonElement element = new JsonElement() {
      @Override
      public JsonElement deepCopy() {
        return null;
      }
    };
    UnsupportedOperationException exception = assertThrows(UnsupportedOperationException.class, element::getAsDouble);
    // The anonymous class simple name is empty string
    assertEquals("", exception.getMessage());
  }
}
```

---

If you want the message to be "JsonElement", you can create a named subclass instead of an anonymous one:

```java
package com.google.gson;
import static org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions.assertEquals;
import static org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions.assertThrows;

import org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;

class JsonElementTest {

  private static class TestJsonElement extends JsonElement {
    @Override
    public JsonElement deepCopy() {
      return null;
    }
  }

  @Test
  void testGetAsDouble_throwsUnsupportedOperationException() {
    JsonElement element = new TestJsonElement();
    UnsupportedOperationException exception = assertThrows(UnsupportedOperationException.class, element::getAsDouble);
    assertEquals("TestJsonElement", exception.getMessage());
  }
}
```

---

If you want the message exactly "JsonElement", you can use reflection to create a proxy or mock the class name, but that is complicated.

